73002fb7763350ebb7b29f2c1a69bb04.text: The mistake was probably made because one of the sponsors of Eintracht Frankfurt is the Euler Group, one of BMW's largest dealers in Germany. The following article should clarify this:

bef090487d01014701f98a67dfe9c6b7.text: Could someone please remove the false claim?

f05397ab09de74d7cb5f17d7d36582d9.text: The German name ''Bayerische Motoren Werke'' is grammatically incorrect; it does not make any sense (<small>and in general, names cannot be translated</small>). This means that the English translation "Bavarian Motor Works" is wrong. Therefore, I recommend that someone removes it. --[[User:Jojhnjoy|Jojhnjoy]] ([[User talk:Jojhnjoy|talk]]) 14:08, 10 September 2017 (UTC)

5ccf970cf8e7c068e5162c33608e8ec9.text: The source cited does not say that BMW translates into English as Bavarian Motor Works. It says that Rapp Motor Works became Bavarian Motor Works. That is a difference.

ffa79de0a1b60e8b28df92e57d2d4d09.text: BMW is a name and you don't translate names.

dc84b552160f20ecf48efa8924f8ce35.text: Bayerische Motoren Werke is grammatically incorrect and you can't translate it. It means something like Bavarian Engines Works or Bavarian Engines, thou shallt work! This doesn't make much sense to me. Bavarian Motor Woek would mean Bayerische Motorenwerke, that's just not the name of the company. While the pronounciation is similar, it is still different.

7b6145490188bd96e8702e8aa672afd8.text: : I don't agree that names can't be translated as a blanket rule. And despite the grammatical quirks of the original German name, I think it is helpful to have a translation of the words available for English readers. Translation is rarely a literal process! Therefore I am in favour of retaining the text. Cheers, [[User:1292simon|1292simon]] ([[User talk:1292simon|talk]]) 10:19, 25 October 2017 (UTC)

ae02a09fd1b913ebc0a101dcec2d328f.text:
::We're not saying the name of BMW in English ''is'' Bayerische Motoren Werke. We're saying those words translate to Bavarian Motor Works, and we have numerous sources in English who use that 'translation', or perhaps 'rough translation', somewhat like a [[transliteration]]. Culturally, the understading of BMW translated this way is widespread. See [[Cleveland CycleWerks]], or [http://www.bwmotorworks.com/ Bidgewater Motor Works], [https://www.waymotorworks.com/ Way Motor Works], [https://www.motorwerke.ca/ etc]. Many sources say this [http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/whats-on/whats-on-news/what-ikea-stand-for-12-13788219][https://www.carkeys.co.uk/news/the-truth-behind-car-brand-names][https://books.google.com/books?id=ZgH9AHSrXu8C&pg=PA21&dq=%22Bayerische+Motoren+Werke%22+bavarian+motor+works&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwijy47GoozXAhVC6mMKHcJpDAUQ6AEINTAD#v=onepage&q=%22Bayerische%20Motoren%20Werke%22%20bavarian%20motor%20works&f=false][http://www.roadandtrack.com/motorsports/a12780515/bill-auberlen-400th-race-bmw-motorsport/]

I haven't seen any sources saying Bavarian Motor Works is incorrect. If we are shown one, we can mention that in the article, alongside the many English sources that accept this as the usual translation. Lacking those sources, it's fine the way it is. --[[User:Dennis Bratland|Dennis Bratland]] ([[User talk:Dennis Bratland|talk]]) 17:21, 25 October 2017 (UTC)

7e129c8f1ef819f8c56b57974cb6b613.text: As I said, you can't just translate it like that. These words don't translate into English as Bavarian Motor Works. I'm not saying that the name in English isn't Bavarian Motor Works, I'm saying that Bayerische Motoren Werke is a name and that it doesn't translate into English as Bavarian Motor Works. It simply can't since it's a name and doesn't make any sense in German. You can safely say that English books refer to BMW as Bavarian Motor Works, there is obvious evidence for that. However, I haven't seen any proof for the translation theory ('BMW translates into English as Bavarian Motor Works'). Several books refer to BMW as Bayerische Motorenwerke. While this is grammatically correct, it isn't their name. I think claiming that BMWs name is wrong is hardly anything someone could prove. But at least I would change the sentence to something like "English language literature refers to BMW as Bavarian Motor Works which translates into German as 'Bayerische Motorenwerke'." The 'translation' though is definitely wrong and none of the cited sources actually says that it translates into English as that, they just refer to it as that.

2c5e1959c45f34b049d996dc519e7b0c.text: :It's called "marketing German" since "Bayrische Motoren Werke" is a compound noun and should be - following the rules of German grammar - hyphenated to "Bayrische Motorenwerke." Unfortunately, there is a rule that word brands don't have to follow grammatical rules which leads to the crap fashion to break up compounds. Just for your information. Best regards, [[User:GeoTrinity|GeoTrinity]] ([[User talk:GeoTrinity|talk]]) 08:13, 9 June 2018 (UTC)

But articles aren't written based on opinions. We get our content from reliable sources. --[[User:Dennis Bratland|Dennis Bratland]] ([[User talk:Dennis Bratland|talk]]) 16:20, 9 June 2018 (UTC)

38c0c8de44f855b8fd62043068f41fab.text: == Content forking does not mean blanking whole sections ==

a9521991cd4b4fad966dc93ddc7422ad.text:
[[WP:Content forking|Content forking]] says: ''"A content fork is the creation of multiple separate articles (or passages within articles) all treating the same subject. Content forks that are created unintentionally result in redundant or conflicting articles and are to be avoided. On the other hand, as an article grows, editors often create summary-style spin-offs or new, linked articles for related material. '' [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=BMW&diff=904972110&oldid=904758175 This mass deletion] is not what that means. It refers you to [[Wikipedia:Summary style]], which details the structure of having parent articles contain summaries of the content in child articles. BMW does not merely refer you to [[History of BMW]]. It ''summarizes'' the history, ''and'' refers you to [[History of BMW]] for the lengthier version.

Having no summary at all is worse than having a history section that is maybe too long. If we can't get a reasonable summary, [[https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=BMW&diff=904972110&oldid=904758175 this] should be reverted pending a better edit. --[[User:Dennis Bratland|Dennis Bratland]] ([[User talk:Dennis Bratland|talk]]) 22:43, 5 July 2019 (UTC)

8e17b20941724963f7258cbfa292b927.text: :It definitely needs a summary. [[User:Toasted Meter|Toasted Meter]] ([[User talk:Toasted Meter|talk]]) 23:48, 5 July 2019 (UTC)

6164887eabdd73a9bd74d1b8b5d9b1df.text:
:*I copied in the lede of [[History of BMW]] as a temporary measure, rather than totally revert 1292simon's deletion. It's lame, and totally avoidable. Why exactly couldn't one have written a summary ''first'', then nuke the content? In other words, if you make an edit, click preview, and what you see is, overall, objectively ''worse'' than the current version, then ''don't'' click publish. If the old version is better, then put your changes in draft form somewhere until you have a version that is better than the old one. This is the essence of [[WP:Editing policy|Editing policy]].

Anyway, both the lede of [[History of BMW]] and [[BMW#History]] could use a good rewrite. --[[User:Dennis Bratland|Dennis Bratland]] ([[User talk:Dennis Bratland|talk]]) 03:33, 6 July 2019 (UTC)
